Exploratory Data Analysis¶

When you're working with the full dataset, perform EDA by loading a small subset of the data and doing basic manipulations within Spark. In this workspace, you are already provided a small subset of data you can explore.

Define Churn¶

Once you've done some preliminary analysis, create a column Churn to use as the label for your model. I suggest using the Cancellation Confirmation events to define your churn, which happen for both paid and free users. As a bonus task, you can also look into the Downgrade events.

Explore Data¶

Once you've defined churn, perform some exploratory data analysis to observe the behavior for users who stayed vs users who churned. You can start by exploring aggregates on these two groups of users, observing how much of a specific action they experienced per a certain time unit or number of songs played.

We could push further the exploration of the dataset but we will instead consider another constructed dataset because of the following considerations:

  • The churners stop using the application earlier than loyal user. Therefore, they will by construction generate less activity.
  • Furthermore, using the dataset as is introduces some data leakage. Actually, we use data of users after they churned. We should instead use the data before they churned.
  • We thus cannot consider the absolute values of the variables as useful features.
  • Instead, we should determine some user profile with actions per unit of time computed on the time they are active on the application.
  • Therefore, we will use the following path:
    • First, we will construct variables that do not produce any leakage
    • Then we will do some data exploration on the constructed data set
    • Finally, we will construct a model to predict the churn

Defining a statistical unit for our study
The goal of the study is to predict whether a user will churn. Since the decision is user-based, we should consider that the elementary unit of our study is a user. We should therefore construct a dataframe indexed by the user where each column is a feature describing how the user interacts with the application.

We will construct the different features below.

Feature construction and data exploration¶

We will now construct some features describing how the users interact with the application.
As stated below, we should avoid features introducing a leakage. The first step is to determine the time of interaction for each user.

Determining the experiment time duration of a user¶

We want to build features such as the number of songs played per unit of time. To do so, we should consider only the period of time a user can perform the action. This means:

  • After the user registered
  • Before the user churned

We therefore need to determine, for each user, those two dates to compute the duration we use to compute the various features.

There are two cases to consider in order to compute the experiment time duration of a user:

  • If the user registered before the first element of the dataframe, we should start its obervation at the beginning of the dataframe. Otherwise, we should use the registration time.
  • If a user did not churn, we should end its observation window at the end of the dataframe. Otherwise, we should use the time of churn.

We will construct the observation window of each user following these rules.

In [15]:
def get_active_hours(df_in = df_valid):
    """
    Computes the duration of the observation time of each user. 
    
    IN:
    df_in : dataframe construted to include the start and end date of each user
    
    OUT:
    df_active_hours : Dataframe with observation window duration of each window in hours
    
    """
    
    ms_per_hour = 3600000
    
    # Get the registration table of each user
    registration_table = df_in.select('userId', 'registration') \
    .groupBy('userId') \
    .agg({'registration':'first'}) \
    .withColumnRenamed('first(registration)', 'registration') \
    
    # For users that registered before the start of the dataFrame, take the start of the dataframe as the 
    # start of the observation window : registration_used
    registration_table = registration_table.withColumn("registration_used", \
        when(registration_table.registration<start_date_default, start_date_default) \
        .otherwise(registration_table.registration))
    
    # Get the last action of a user and its time stamp
    df_end_state = df_in.select('userId', 'page', 'ts') \
    .groupBy('userId') \
    .agg({'ts':'max', 'page':'last'}) \
    .withColumnRenamed('last(page)', 'last_action') \
    .withColumnRenamed('max(ts)', 'last_ts') \
    
    # For users that did not churn, take the end of the observation window as the end of the dataframe
    df_end_state = df_end_state.withColumn("last_ts_used", \
        when(df_end_state.last_action == 'Cancellation Confirmation', df_end_state.last_ts)
        .otherwise(end_date_default))
    
    # Join two tables
    df_obs_window = registration_table.join(df_end_state, on=['userId'], how='left') 
    
    # Get the observation windows durations for each users
    df_obs_window = df_obs_window.withColumn('active_hours', \
     ( df_obs_window.last_ts_used - df_obs_window.registration_used  ) / ms_per_hour )

    df_active_hours = df_obs_window.select('userId', 'active_hours')
        
    return df_active_hours

df_active_hours = get_active_hours(df_valid)

Feature construction : user activity per unit of time¶

In [16]:
def add_page_feature(page_feature_name, df_in, df_events = df_valid):
    """
    Add the specific feature 'page_feature_name' to the df_in dataframe. 
    The df_in dataframe is indexed by the userId and contains actions per hours. 
    The function computes the total number of times the action 'page_feature_name' id executed, and divide the value
    by the obervation window duration of the user. 
    
    IN:
    page_feature_name : the feature to be considered.
    df_in : The df_in dataframe indexed by the userId and containing actions per hours. 
    df_events : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    df_in completed with the page_feature_name column     
    """
    
    df_count = df_events.select('userId', 'page').filter(df_events.page == page_feature_name).groupBy('userId').count()
    df_in = df_in.join(df_count, on=['userId'], how='left')
    df_in = df_in.withColumn('_'.join(page_feature_name.split())+'_per_hour', df_in['count']/df_in['active_hours'] )
    df_in = df_in.drop('count')
    df_in = df_in.fillna(0)
    
    return df_in
In [17]:
def add_num_actions_hour_feature(df_in, df_events = df_valid):
    """
    Count the total number of interactions per hour for the different users.  
    The df_in dataframe is indexed by the userId and contains actions per hours. 
    
    IN:
    df_in : The df_in dataframe indexed by the userId and containing actions per hours. 
    df_events : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    df_in completed with the act_per_hour column giving the total number of interactions per hour for the different users.      
    """
    
    df_count = df_events.select('userId', 'page').groupBy('userId').count()
    df_in = df_in.join(df_count, on=['userId'], how='left')
    df_in = df_in.withColumn('act_per_hour', df_in['count']/df_in['active_hours'] )
    df_in = df_in.drop('count')
    
    return df_in

Features construction : gender table and churn label¶

def get_churn_table(df_in = df_valid):
    """
    Compute a table indexed by userId identifying the users that churned.
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    A dataframe indexed by userId identifying the users that churned.
    """
    
    churn_table = df_in.select('userId', 'Churn').distinct()
    churn_table = churn_table.groupBy('userId').max().withColumnRenamed('max(Churn)', 'Churn')
    return churn_table
In [19]:
def get_gender_table(df_in = df_valid):
    """
    Compute a table indexed by userId identifying the gender of the users.
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    A dataframe indexed by userId identifying the gender of the users.
    """
        
    gender_table = df_valid.select('userId', 'gender').distinct()
    gender_table = gender_table.withColumn('gender_int', (gender_table['gender'] == 'F').cast(IntegerType()))
    gender_table = gender_table.drop('gender')
    gender_table = gender_table.withColumnRenamed('gender_int', 'gender')
    return gender_table

Feature construction : user activity per visit¶

In [20]:
# User defined function equal to 1 when the page is 'Home'
ishome_function = udf(lambda ishome : int(ishome == 'Home'), IntegerType())

user_window = Window \
    .partitionBy('userID') \
    .orderBy(desc('ts')) \
    .rangeBetween(Window.unboundedPreceding, 0)

def get_num_songs_per_visit(df_in = df_valid, user_window = user_window):
    """
    Gives the average number of songs played per visit for a given user.
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    user_window : user specific window indexed by the time. 
    
    OUT:
    songs_per_visit : A dataframe indexed by userId identifying the average number of songs played per visit.
    """
    
    cusum = df_in.filter((df_in.page == 'NextSong') | (df_in.page == 'Home')) \
        .select('userID', 'page', 'ts') \
        .withColumn('homevisit', ishome_function(col('page'))) \
        .withColumn('period', Fsum('homevisit').over(user_window))

    songs_per_visit = cusum.filter((cusum.page == 'NextSong')) \
        .groupBy('userID', 'period') \
        .agg({'period':'count'}) \
        .select('userId', 'count(period)') \
        .groupBy('userId') \
        .mean() \
        .withColumnRenamed('avg(count(period))', 'songs_per_visit')
    
    return songs_per_visit

def get_num_items_per_visit(df_in = df_valid):
    """
    Gives the average number of interactions per visit for a given user.
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    songs_per_visit : A dataframe indexed by userId identifying the average number of songs played per visit.
    """
    
    items_per_visit = df_valid.groupby(['userId', 'sessionId'])\
    .agg(Fmax(col('itemInSession')).alias('num_items'))\
    .groupby('userId').agg(avg(col('num_items')).alias('items_per_visit'))
    
    return items_per_visit

def get_num_hours_per_visit(df_in = df_valid):
    """
    Gives the average visit duration in hours for a given user.
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    
    OUT:
    hours_per_visit : A dataframe indexed by userId identifying average visit duration in hours.
    """
    
    ms_per_hour = 3600000
    
    hours_per_visit = df_valid.groupby(['userId', 'sessionId'])\
    .agg(Fmin(col('ts')).alias('session_start'), Fmax(col('ts')).alias('session_end'))\
    .groupby('userId')\
    .agg((avg(col('session_end')-col('session_start'))/ms_per_hour).alias('hours_per_visit'))
    
    return hours_per_visit

Combine all previous functions to get the final dataframe with all features¶

In [23]:
selected_page_features = ['Thumbs Down', 'Home', 'Roll Advert', 'Save Settings', \
                          'About', 'Settings', 'Add to Playlist', 'Add Friend', 'NextSong', 'Thumbs Up', \
                          'Help', 'Error']

def get_features(df_in=df_valid, page_features = selected_page_features):
    """
    Combine all previous functions to get the final dataframe with all features
    
    IN:
    df_in : the original (cleaned) dataframe containing all the events.
    page_features : the 'page' features we will consider
    
    OUT:
    df_features : A dataframe indexed by userId with all features we want to consider.
    """
        
    df_active_hours = get_active_hours()
    
    df_features = df_active_hours
    for feature in page_features:
        df_features = add_page_feature(feature, df_features)
        
    df_features = add_num_actions_hour_feature(df_features)    
        
    songs_per_visit = get_num_songs_per_visit(df_in)
    df_features = df_features.join(songs_per_visit, on=['userId'], how='left')
        
    items_per_visit = get_num_items_per_visit(df_in)
    df_features = df_features.join(items_per_visit, on=['userId'], how='left')    
        
    hours_per_visit = get_num_hours_per_visit(df_in)
    df_features = df_features.join(hours_per_visit, on=['userId'], how='left')    
    
    gender_table = get_gender_table(df_in)
    df_features = df_features.join(gender_table, on=['userId'], how='left')
        
    churn_table = get_churn_table(df_in)
    df_features = df_features.join(churn_table, on=['userId'], how='left')
    
    df_features = df_features.drop('active_hours')
    
    return df_features

#  F1 score evaluator
class F1_score(Evaluator):
    """
    F1 score evaluation to be used for model evaluation and grid-search
    
    """

    def __init__(self, predictionCol = "prediction", labelCol="label"):
        self.predictionCol = predictionCol
        self.labelCol = labelCol

    def _evaluate(self, dataset):
        
        eps = 0.0001
        
        # F1 score 
        true_pos = dataset.where((dataset.label == 1) & (dataset.prediction == 1)).count()
        false_pos = dataset.where((dataset.label == 0) & (dataset.prediction == 1)).count()
        true_neg = dataset.where((dataset.label == 0) & (dataset.prediction == 0)).count()
        false_neg = dataset.where((dataset.label == 1) & (dataset.prediction == 0)).count()
        
        # Add epsilon to prevent division by zero
        precision = true_pos / float(true_pos + false_pos + eps)
        recall = true_pos / float(true_pos + false_neg + eps)
        
        f1 = 2 * precision * recall / float(precision + recall + eps)
        
        return f1

    def isLargerBetter(self):
        return True
